Title/Message:
Enhancement of validation.

Many data structure in Fishtest contain references to a run
objects. Naively validating such data structures means that we
are also validating the embedded run objects, which is wasteful
as these are already validated elsewhere.

The latest version of vtjson makes it possible to change
subschemas during validation.

In this PR we define the cache_schema as

cache_schema = {
    run_id: {
        "run": set_label(runs_schema, "runs_schema"),
	"is_changed": bool,
        "last_sync_time": ufloat,
        "last_access_time": ufloat,
    },
}

and we perform validation via

validate(cache_schema, self.run_cache, name="run_cache", subs={"runs_schema": dict})

Requires upgrade of vtjson.

Title/Message:
More dynamically updated aggregated data.

We introduce two new aggregated variables: committed_games
and total_games. Both are used in "request_task", the former a
being bit more important since it may be computed several times.

Also: some code refactoring. The functions with name
"compute_..." that compute the various types of aggregated data
are now grouped together in schemas.py.

Also: we have updated the cache_schema as the field
"last_scavenge_time" is no longer used. We use the cache_schema
to validate the cache during initialization, the idea being that
an unused schema will quickly suffer from bitrot and will hence
also lose its documentation value.

Title/Message:
Bug fix for #2030

With the present code a finished run with run["cores"]>0 will
never be evicted from the cache. This is not a legal
condition but it happened in the past because of race conditions.

This explains why #2030 seemed to create more unvalidated runs.
The illegal runs become more and more likely to be selected for
validation as they are not evicted and eventually dominate the
cache.

Author: Michel Van den Bergh

Title/Message:
Do not evict a run from the cache which has active tasks.

A dead task (a task which has not been updated for 360s) will only
be scavenged if it belongs to a run in the cache. However clean
runs are evicted from the cache after 300s. So if the run does
not get new tasks, for example because it has low priority, the
dead tasks remain unscavenged until somebody explicitly looks at
the run (this pulls the run back in the cache).

Obviously it is not nice that dead tasks are not scavenged as soon
as possible. Moreover the fact that the behaviour of the server
is affected by executing a GET request is a violation of the HTTP
specs.
Author: Michel Van den Bergh

Title/Message:
Every three minutes validate a random run from the cache.

The reason for this PR is that before introducing more dynamic
updates we would like to verify that the dynamic updates of
run["workers"] and run["cores"] introduced in
https://github.com/official-stockfish/fishtest/pull/2010
are bug free.

In order to facilitate the use of periodic timers in Fishtest
we have introduced a new scheduler in utils.py which may be
interesting in its own right.

Currently the timers defined are the cache flush timer and the
timer introduced in this PR.

Title/Message:
Send heartbeat only when needed

this changes slightly how the heartbeat works:
Instead of sending it every 120s regularly, only send it if the last update to the server is 120s ago.

For example, in a case like this:
```
2024-05-19 11:44:59.219186+00:00 : run: 664937bcb8fa20e74c39f42e task: 126 size: 416 tc: 10+0.1 concurrency: 7 threads: 1 [ sprt : 800000 ]
2024-05-19 11:46:58.900077+00:00 :   1.02 ms (s)   152.93 ms (w)  https://tests.stockfishchess.org:443/api/beat
2024-05-19 11:48:55.849837+00:00 :   2.16 ms (s)   144.34 ms (w)  https://tests.stockfishchess.org:443/api/update_task
2024-05-19 11:48:59.073522+00:00 :   1.55 ms (s)   160.57 ms (w)  https://tests.stockfishchess.org:443/api/beat
2024-05-19 11:50:46.055023+00:00 :   2.91 ms (s)   172.30 ms (w)  https://tests.stockfishchess.org:443/api/update_task
2024-05-19 11:50:59.258581+00:00 :   3.02 ms (s)   149.73 ms (w)  https://tests.stockfishchess.org:443/api/beat
2024-05-19 11:52:28.238362+00:00 :   3.37 ms (s)   145.20 ms (w)  https://tests.stockfishchess.org:443/api/update_task
2024-05-19 11:52:59.421249+00:00 :   1.31 ms (s)   147.74 ms (w)  https://tests.stockfishchess.org:443/api/beat
2024-05-19 11:54:23.428656+00:00 :   2.77 ms (s)   155.25 ms (w)  https://tests.stockfishchess.org:443/api/update_task
2024-05-19 11:54:59.597397+00:00 :   1.61 ms (s)   144.52 ms (w)  https://tests.stockfishchess.org:443/api/beat
2024-05-19 11:56:18.618653+00:00 :   3.33 ms (s)   145.78 ms (w)  https://tests.stockfishchess.org:443/api/update_task
2024-05-19 11:56:59.757185+00:00 :   1.40 ms (s)   143.08 ms (w)  https://tests.stockfishchess.org:443/api/beat
2024-05-19 11:58:10.802213+00:00 :   1.47 ms (s)   152.79 ms (w)  https://tests.stockfishchess.org:443/api/update_task
2024-05-19 11:58:59.927009+00:00 :   1.24 ms (s)   141.62 ms (w)  https://tests.stockfishchess.org:443/api/beat
2024-05-19 12:00:01.989951+00:00 :   2.97 ms (s)   144.60 ms (w)  https://tests.stockfishchess.org:443/api/update_task
2024-05-19 12:01:00.095270+00:00 :   1.50 ms (s)   154.71 ms (w)  https://tests.stockfishchess.org:443/api/beat
2024-05-19 12:01:54.193067+00:00 :   2.85 ms (s)   143.12 ms (w)  https://tests.stockfishchess.org:443/api/update_task
2024-05-19 12:03:00.267084+00:00 :   0.55 ms (s)   151.15 ms (w)  https://tests.stockfishchess.org:443/api/beat
2024-05-19 12:03:56.383263+00:00 :   2.98 ms (s)   152.39 ms (w)  https://tests.stockfishchess.org:443/api/update_task
2024-05-19 12:05:00.453999+00:00 :   3.06 ms (s)   145.32 ms (w)  https://tests.stockfishchess.org:443/api/beat
```

Essentially none of the beats needs to be sent, as the server is getting updates to the task more frequently than once every 2min anyway.

With this patch we have a following api log on a high core worker:
```
2024-05-19 14:19:13.526943+00:00 : run: 664a027fae57c1758ac5b4ee task: 286 size: 486 tc: 60+0.6 concurrency: 25 threads: 1 [ sprt : 800000 ]
2024-05-19 14:21:13.421935+00:00 :   1.54 ms (s)   169.11 ms (w)  https://tests.stockfishchess.org:443/api/beat
2024-05-19 14:23:13.680019+00:00 :   1.06 ms (s)   136.66 ms (w)  https://tests.stockfishchess.org:443/api/beat
2024-05-19 14:23:44.292362+00:00 :   3.54 ms (s)   170.59 ms (w)  https://tests.stockfishchess.org:443/api/update_task
2024-05-19 14:23:58.479615+00:00 :   3.40 ms (s)   168.31 ms (w)  https://tests.stockfishchess.org:443/api/update_task

```
i.e. as soon as the games start finishing, the heartbeast is no longer sent.

While the beat api is cheap, it is the most frequent api call, so saving a few is a good thing.

Title/Message:
Fully dynamic updates of run["cores"] and run["workers"].

We have everywhere replaced

task["active"] = False

by

set_inactive(task_id, run)

which does the required bookkeeping under the task_lock.

The intention is that the task_lock will only be held for a very
short time. So in request_task we only grab it at the moment
when we actually add a task to the run (currently it is held
during the whole invocation of request_task).

If it works then this PR can serve as a model for other types of
bookkeeping like the number of committed games.

Other change:

We start the cache timer in __init__.py at application start up
instead of during the first invocation of buffer().

Title/Message:
Do not flag a worker as a duplicate of itself.

It may happen that a worker fails to update a task because
of server issues. It will retry 5 times and then ask for a new
task. But the server will not have marked the original task
as inactive. So before this PR the worker will be flagged as
a duplicate of itself and will be denied a new task
for some time.

In this PR we simply mark the original task as inactive
and continue.

Log long worker names when rejecting a duplicate worker name.

This is to debug sequences of rejections such as this one

Apr 24 22:26:50 tests.stockfishchess.org pserve[24847]: Request_task: There is already a worker running with name "ChessDBCN-11cores-ccd4f156" which sent an update 70 seconds ago
Apr 24 22:28:46 tests.stockfishchess.org pserve[24847]: Request_task: There is already a worker running with name "ChessDBCN-11cores-ccd4f156" which sent an update 50 seconds ago
Apr 24 22:29:42 tests.stockfishchess.org pserve[24847]: Request_task: There is already a worker running with name "ChessDBCN-11cores-ccd4f156" which sent an update 106 seconds ago
Apr 24 22:32:21 tests.stockfishchess.org pserve[24847]: Request_task: There is already a worker running with name "ChessDBCN-11cores-ccd4f156" which sent an update 70 seconds ago

I conjecture that this is a sequence of events where a worker connects,

Title/Message:
Avoid timeouts for GitHub diffs

This allows for users to use their own limited GitHub tokens to avoid exceeding the GitHub rate limit when viewing github diffs (mainly useful to approvers), which is set at 60 requests per hour for unauthenticated users. By using this token, you can surpass the standard rate limit, extending it beyond the 5000 requests per hour limit. You can find more information about GitHub's rate limits here.

It's important to note that this token will not be stored in a database but rather in your local storage. This ensures security and reduces the risk of unauthorized access.

The token should only be granted read-only permissions and limited access. This ensures that it can only be used for viewing content and not for making any modifications or accessing sensitive information.

Instructions:
1- Access the link here.
2- Generate a new token.
3- Set the Repository access to "All Repositories".
4- In the Permissions section, grant only the "Read" permission for contents, leaving all other permissions as "No Access".
5- Once generated, copy the token.
6- Save the token into the input field

the link to add/change the token https://tests.stockfishchess.org/user

Also this has many optimizations and bug fixes.

Title/Message:
Implement bulk streaming of tasks PGNs for a run

This commit adds a feature that streams PGNs of a run, significantly reducing
the server's CPU/RAM usage. The API now returns a gzipped PGN, constructed by
chaining all the run's gzipped PGNs, which is streamed to the client.

Key changes:
1. update 'api_download_run_pgns' in api.py, which handles the request for
downloading the PGN of the run. It fetches the PGNs using the
'get_run_pgns' method from the RunDb class, and returns a gzipped response
   ```
   wget https://test.stockfishchess.org/api/run_pgns/<run_id>.pgn.gz
   ```
2. add 'GeneratorAsFileReader' class in util.py that provides a file-like
interface for a generator, enabling chanked reading
3. modify the 'get_run_pgns' method in rundb.py to return a
'GeneratorAsFileReader' object that yields each gzipped PGN file for the run

Note: the `gunzip on;` directive must be removed from the nginx configuration.

Improvement suggested by @peregrineshahin

Title/Message:
Improve the action schema.

The new schema is functionally equivalent to the old schema
but the non-validation messages are much better.

Validating

{"action": "failed_task", "message": "It's going well!"}

against the old schema may yield (it is not deterministic)

action['worker'] is missing and action['worker'] is missing and
action['worker'] is missing and action['action']
(value:'failed_task') is not equal to 'system_event' and
action['action'] (value:'failed_task') is not equal to 'new_run'
and action['action'] (value:'failed_task') is not equal to
'upload_nn' and action['action'] (value:'failed_task') is not
equal to 'modify_run' and action['action'] (value:'failed_task')
is not equal to 'delete_run' and action['action']
(value:'failed_task') is not equal to 'stop_run' and
action['action'] (value:'failed_task') is not equal to
'finished_run' and action['action'] (value:'failed_task') is not
equal to 'approve_run' and action['action'] (value:'failed_task')
is not equal to 'purge_run' and action['user'] is missing and
action['user'] is missing and action['worker'] is missing and
action['action'] (value:'failed_task') is not equal to
'log_message'

whereas the new schema gives

action['worker'] is missing

Requires upgrading the vtjson package.

Title/Message:
Introduce log_message action.

This may be used to give internal errors in the logic of

This action is currently used in two places:

- if a finished run does not validate;

updated results and the computed results in a finished run.

worker errors which happen before a task is requested (e.g.
failure to be able to run cutechess-cli).

an error string on non-validation, by the more Pythonic

Title/Message:
Start the make command in its own session on posix.

If make receives SIGINT then it does not kill its children.
This is particularly visible during linking which takes quite
a bit of time to finish.

By putting make into its own session and sending the signal
to the corresponding process group, make will finish immediately,
even during linking.

I tested that ctrl-C in the terminal still works, even if the
worker is started from a script.
Author: Michel Van den Bergh

Title/Message:
Shut down the worker quickly after receiving SIGINT.

To test this PR (on Linux, see below) one may run the worker
in one terminal and during compiling send a SIGINT or SIGTERM
to the python process from another terminal (e.g. via
kill <PID-python>). A worker running master will only stop
when the make command finishes. If the worker runs this PR
then it will stop immediately and clean up.

This PR currently has no effect on Windows as the mechanism
for terminating processes is different. Probably there is
also no need for this PR on that OS.

Title/Message:
Introduce a schema for the rundb.

Validation is done after the creation of runs and before writing
finished runs to disk. If a finished run fails validation then
this is logged but the run is otherwise treated normally.

No attempt has been made to make the schema as tight as possible.
For example most numbers should be positive but this constraint
is ignored by the schema. The main purpose of the schema is to
document the structure of the rundb. The reason it is also used
for validation in some cases is to ensure that if the
structure of the rundb changes then the schema is updated to
reflect this change.

For a description of the schema format see the README.md file
of https://github.com/vdbergh/vtjson

The validation code is included in this PR but it can be
installed as an independent package via

pip install vtjson

Validating a run with 500 tasks (which is a lot these days)
takes 12 ms on an AWS t2.micro using Python 3.11.

Title/Message:
Implement efficient PGN upload and bulk download

The previous worker code posted the PGN to the server in a
zlib-compressed format. This required the server to decompress
the data before serving the PGN as text, resulting in significant CPU
and network overhead. Furthermore, a bulk download of all PGNs from a run
necessitated additional CPU overhead for compression.

The updated worker code posts a gzip file containing the PGN text
to the server, leading to more efficient handling on the server side:
- for single PGN downloads, the server simply serves
  the gzipped PGN retrieved from MongoDB. All modern browsers
  decompress the gzip file client side, so the user will get the
  pgn as text file. nginx can be configured to decompress on the fly
  the gzip content for a client that is not declaring his compression
  capability.
- for bulk PGN downloads, the server writes a tar file
  containing all the gzipped PGNs retrieved from MongoDB
  ```
  wget https://test.stockfishchess.org/api/run_pgns/<run_id>.pgns.tar
  ```
- gzip module uses zlib, no change for the compression ratio.

@peregrineshahin wrote the bulk download code
in https://github.com/official-stockfish/fishtest/pull/1804

Retire "pgn_100" api.

closes https://github.com/official-stockfish/fishtest/issues/1801

Title/Message:
Replace deprecated `distutils` package

The package `distutils` is deprecated since python 3.10
and it is scheduled to be removed with python 3.12, see:
https://docs.python.org/3.12/whatsnew/3.12.html
https://github.com/python/cpython/issues/92584

`shutil.copytree()` is able to copy the source directory tree to an existing
destination directory only from python 3.8 (parameter `dirs_exist_ok=True`),
for python < 3.8 still use `distutils.dir_util.copy_tree()`

While here:
- create in a safe way the temporary directory used for the update
- deal with possible download problems

Title/Message:
Remove cached binaries on worker startup

as the user could change the compiler at worker startup time (e.g. clang vs gcc),
the binary cache might contain binaries compiled with a different compiler
than the ones generated by the worker. As different compilers lead to binaries of
different speed, test results could be biased, unless we assure that the same compiler
is used for both base and new test.

This patch just clears the binary cache once at worker startup,
leaving the caching mechanism unchanged otherwise.

fixes https://github.com/glinscott/fishtest/issues/1666

Title/Message:
Reduce ITP with number of active tests per user

given some excessive number of active tests by some users, this patch reduces itp based on the number of active tests.

The formula used is `itp *= 36.0 / (36.0 + count * count)`

This reduces slowly the itp for a number of tests smaller than 6, and rapidly afterwards.
For 3 active tests, the itp is 80%, for 6 active tests, the itp is 50%, for 15 active tests it is down to 13%.

For a maximum share of fishtest... have 6 tests in queue.

Title/Message:
Standardize usage of "last_updated" name

In the codebase, the key "last_updated" is consistently used as
a datetime object. However, in "delta_update_users.py",
it was used as a string representation.

This change standardizes the usage of "last_updated" by ensuring that
it is always used as a datetime object. As a result, it is necessary
to run "delta_update_users.py" in full scan mode to rebuild the
"users_cache" and "top_month" collections with the new key names.
Author: ppigazzini

Title/Message:
Rewrite "delta_update_users.py"

The previous version of the script had two major issues:
1. it loaded only one run ID from the deltas collection without any sorting
   criterion. Since there is no guarantee that the returned natural order
   is the insertion order, this could result in a very inaccurate contribution
   calculation in the first update scan after a full scan, when the deltas
   collection contains all the finished run IDs.
2. the run, with the ID loaded from the deltas collection, could switch
   to active status (e.g., after a purge).
   This resulted in failing to stop the processing and double counting
   of already processed finished runs from the last 30 days.

Changes:
- load and save the IDs of all the processed finished runs in
  deltas collection, python checks if a key is in a dict in O(1)
- in update scan mode, for the total contribution:
  - skip processing of any finished run with ID in deltas
  - stop processing after hitting 10 finished runs with ID in deltas
- lazy load the data from collections to lower the RAM footprint
- simplify the algorithms
- add comments

Note that the update scan is not perfect:
- it does not account for the additional contribution of runs that have
  switched from finished to unfinished and back to finished in the meantime.
- it underestimates the top month contribution compared to the full scan
  due to the exit condition.

Title/Message:
More robust wake up from sleep.

I occasionally still observe duplicate notifications on ipad after
wake up. I think the reason is that one tab may sleep before a
fetch and another thread may sleep during the "async_sleep(1500)".
This results in a race.

We catch this by checking the actual time slept. If it is > 90s
then we cancel the fetch.

One would like to reduce the 90s but this would be defeated by the
fact that timers on Chrome fire only once per minute in inactive
tabs.

There is also some nice refactoring. The function async_sleep
can now be used as

let t = await async_sleep(delay_ms);

where t is the amount of time (in ms) that is actually slept.

Increase cache time for user creditials

increases the time to 2min, which should halve the time spent in authetication.
Authentication happes quite often, i.e. each worker connects every minute,
and is one of the more expensive calls for the critical pserve.

The PR also clears the cache on writes to the database,

as long as the cache is cleared on every db write. This has not yet been implemented,

Title/Message:
Speedup in tests_view for long list of tasks

The code was very CPU-intensive for runs with long task lists:
- checking that a dictionary is contained in a list of dictionaries is expensive
- the code performed O(n^2) checks with n the length of the list

Improvements:
- check very rare events first (bad task)
- check if the task is contained in the first list by comparing idx and
  the length of the first list
- some code refactoring
Author: ppigazzini

Title/Message:

Author: Michel Van den Bergh

Title/Message:
Regularly purge stale notifications.

Stale notifications are notifications for finished runs.
They are harmless but they needlessly load the server (forever with
the current implementation).

Stale notifications can for example be created by subscribing to a
finished run in a browser tab that was not refreshed.

Purging will happen every 5.5 hours on average and uses the
active_runs api to detect finished but still subscribed runs.

Title/Message:
Reduce "LTC only" thread threshold

Several workers in the last month between 30 and 32 threads have fallen afoul of the well-established cutechess bugs in many-threaded contexts. Altho most such workers run fine, we currently have no server-side filtering of garbage results, nor any worker-side workaround, so this is the best we've got. Update it now to reduce future garbage with the least current effort.

As stated, most workers in the 29-32 thread run fine, but those that don't are a significant problem. To the best of my knowledge, all workers at 28 or less have run fine so far. It's certainly easy to adjust this again in the future.

Title/Message:
Improve sorting of unfinished runs according to priority

Try pre-including worker cores in cores/itp priority estimate

At present, STC tasks appear to systematically have higher cores/itp
than LTC tasks. If this is due to low workers-per-test granularity
issues, this is the fix.

Tweak itp assignment: average oldcores+newcores, but always at least one worker

Per the code comment:
Tests with low itp/workers-per-test can cause granularity issues. If
we simply use oldcores-per-itp, then low-core tests will be overweighted
when they're assigned large workers. If we simply use newcores-per-itp,
then low-core tests will be underweighted when they're *not* assigned
large workers. Split the difference by splitting the difference, and
also ensuring at least one worker at all times.

closes https://github.com/glinscott/fishtest/pull/1558

Title/Message:
Reduce latency of LTC relative to STC

Adjust the TC power law exponent to make base LTC TP of 4x STC TP,
with the goal of reducing LTC latency to only 1.5x STC latency.

With the recent of busyness of fishtest (a good thing IMO), the
current LTC latency of sqrt(6) ~ 2.5x is making for painfully long
feedback time, potentially causing authors to submit more
later-unnecessary STC tests rather than wait for LTC results. The
latency is actually more than 2.5x on average since LTC elo bounds
are higher as well, requiring more games at the same elo performance
(on average).

This adjustment reduces LTC base latency from 2.5 to 1.5, which
should hopefully reduce the number of red-herring STC submissions
as the test result feedback loop tightens up.

I also tweaked the LLR bonus TP, reducing it slightly on both ends,
but I'm not nearly as attached to this as to the exponent change.
(1.37/0.63 new max/min vs old max/min 1.59/0.41)

Also, don't boost shorter-than-STC latency.

Title/Message:
Asynchronous network upload

To avoid duplicated netowrk entries in the DB
was forced a synchronous upload, see:
https://github.com/glinscott/fishtest/pull/757

An easy way to enable to avoid duplicate entries is to
look up the network in the DB just before adding the entry.

This PR speed up the upload process and reduces possible race conditions
checking for duplicate files on the file server as well, raising
the appropriate HTTP errors if necessary.

Other changes:
 - use a fixed path for the POST (usually the {id} is used in PUT and
   DELETE)
 - use a multipart form POST to upload the network.
   In this way the file server can use an UploadFile object
   that uses in a smart way the RAM for big data

Requirements:
 - update of the file server
 - adding a "/" in the fishtest.upload

Title/Message:
Do not delete a task after purging but mark it as bad.

With the current code a purged task is deleted from the task
list. This means that the numbering of tasks changes.

One consequence of this is that links to tasks in the event log
may become invalid.

Another issue is that task_id's held by the worker become invalid.
This is unlikely to cause problems but it is still not nice
and could lead to bugs later.

In this PR we mark a purged task as bad. For safety we also make
it non-active and set all its stats to zero.

Title/Message:
Compute sri hashes of worker files and compare with master.

The sri hashes of the current worker files are stored in a
file "sri.txt". This file is updated each time the worker
runs, and it can also be updated manually with

python worker.py --only_config

CI is used to enforce that the file sri.txt matches the worker files
during pushes or pull requests.

The worker will also download the master sri.txt (currently not existing)

https://raw.githubusercontent.com/glinscott/fishtest/master/worker/sri.txt

and check if the hashes in that file coincide with the sri hashes
of the current worker. If not then a message is printed on the terminal.
A tainted worker is not stopped but the flag worker_info['modified'] is
set to True. In a subsequent PR the server will use this information
in the event log messages (for debugging purposes).

In order to fix the race condition between the update of the master
worker on GitHub and the update of the Fishtest server (which pulls its
code from GitHub), the file sri.txt contains the version number of the
worker. We ignore the master sri.txt if its version is higher
than the version of the running worker.

Title/Message:
Adapt to new MDN standard with explicit SameSite

Explicitly set SameSite to Lax to treat FireFox warning (in the browser console) of new Cookie standard when clicking on the "finished button"

- Lax is the default we already have but setting it explicitly to make cookies standardized for most browsers and treat the warning
- Lax option allows HTTP cookie transmission which is what we have for buttons state and is convenient for Dev purposes in testing on other devices in the same network
- Note that any sensitive cookies introduced in the future should be flagged as secured and not Lax but these button-states are not sensitive data and we don't provide them to third parties

For any new use of cookies in sensitive data,
see the options available at: https://developer.mozilla.org/en-US/docs/Web/HTTP/Headers/Set-Cookie

Title/Message:
Try a backup copy if the downloaded cutechess-cli is not working.

Logic:

1) Check if cutechess-cli exists and is working.

2) If not: download it.

3) Check if downloaded cutechess-cli is working.

4) If not: try to restore a backup copy.

5) If successful check if the backup copy is working.

6) If not: bail out.

Do not treat MacOS specially in the updater.

Move cutechess-cli setup to worker.py so that it is done
only once.

Title/Message:
New shot at generating a stable default uuid_prefix for workers..

Currently the algorithm for the default uuid_prefix uses the MAC
address. But the MAC address is unstable on modern OSes. Moreover
uuid.getnode() seems to be buggy on a number of systems and simply
returns a random number. This needs ugly and fragile workarounds.

The new algorithm uses:

1) the machine_id (a uuid generated during system install);
2) the absolute path of the worker;
3) a random seed which is saved in the config file.

This algorithm can be defeated by cloning a cloud instance with
an installed worker.

This seems like a niche case. But if it turns out that it does happen
then we can work around it by detecting the resulting duplicate
prefix and generating a new seed.

Title/Message:
Set SPSA A proportional to the total iterations

The A parameter avoids instability in early SPSA iterations,
the seminal paper suggests to set it at 10% of the total iterations.
fishtest used the default A=3000 (10% of the default 30000 iterations)
that is too small for SPSA ran with 250-500k iterations.

- Ask for the "A_ratio", decimal in range [0; 1], in the new SPSA test
form.
- Set as default value the 10% of total iterations.
- Compute the "A_ratio" when rescheduling a SPSA.
- Backward compatibility saving in the DB "A = A_ratio * iterations"

Title/Message:
Replace "a" with "r" in SPSA table

The fishtest SPSA implementation uses "r = a / c**2" instead of the
textbook "a" parameter, so write "r" in the SPSA table.

- SPSA evaluation step:
Play a mini match between these 2 values of the parameter to be optimized:
```
tetha + c * flip
tetha - c * flip
```

- SPSA update step:
```
theta = theta + (c * r) * flip * (W - L)

theta : value of the parameter
c     : variation applied to the parameter
c * r : fraction of c used to update the parameter
flip  : random -1 or +1
W - L : difference between Wins and Losses
```

Title/Message:
Allow expressions involving max for concurrency and max_memory.

Examples:

--concurrency max-1            # leave 1 core for the OS
--concurrency min(4,max/2)     # reserve half of the cores for
                                 Fishtest with a maximum of 4

We compute the defaults for concurrency and max_memory in the configfile.

A freshly minted configfile now contains

concurrency = 1 if max==1 else min(3, max-1)
max_memory = max/2

If the expression for concurrency does not contain "max",
concurrency is limited to max_cpu_count-1. Otherwise it is limited to
max_cpu_count.

Title/Message:
Fix formula for disabling "Next" button in pager.

I think the format of the pager has changed over
the years. As a result the code for disabling
the Next button is no longer correct.

In this PR the Next button is disabled when

page_idx>=(num_finished_runs - 1) // page_size

where page_idx=<current page no>-1.

Examples:

num_finished_runs=75, page_size=25

We have 3 full pages. So Next should be disabled if the current
page number is 3. I.e. if page_idx=2. This is what the
formula gives.

num_finished_runs=76, page_size=25

Now we have 4 pages, the last one containing 1 run. So Next
should be disabled when page_idx=3, which is again what the formula gives.

Note:

Since we currently do not exclude deleted runs from our
queries, but filter them out later instead, it is theoretically
possible to have empty pages. This is quite unlikely however since
deleted runs are very rare.

Title/Message:
List the pentanomial draw ratio on the raw stats page.

The pentanomial draw ratio is the ratio of DD+WL+LW results
(i.e. non-decisive game pairs).

When the probability of double wins/losses is low then
normalized Elo may be approximated as

nElo = sqrt(2)*Elo/sqrt(1-d)

Here Elo denotes logistic Elo and d is the pentanomial draw ratio.

Title/Message:
Some tweaks around option handling.

1) This PR started by trying to fix.

https://github.com/glinscott/fishtest/issues/1184

It turned that there are fundamental issues with the
semantics of --use_all_cores. So it was decided
to deprecate --use_all_cores and to introduce
--concurrency max as a clearly defined substitute for
--use_all_cores True.

Some backward compatibility is temporarily retained, but
--use_all_cores will be removed in the future to simplify
the worker code.

2) We now strictly validate config file entries and command
line parameters.

In particular we make sure that in the options object returned by
setup_parameters() all attributes have the expected type. This
makes the downstream code simpler.

3) We switch from optparse to argparse. optparse is deprecated.

4) We now check, at the startup of the worker, that the
password, supplied via the config file or on the command line,
is correct. If it is not then we present a password dialog.

This validation step is skipped when the flag --no_validation is
present on the command line. In combination with --only_config
this is useful when there is no network access.

5) --only_config is now a flag. In contrast --fleet remains
a boolean since all three possibilities (True/False of omitted)
are meaningful.

closes #1189
Author: Michel Van den Bergh

Title/Message:
Do not make dead tasks visible by default in the events log.

This is similar to system events.

A dead task may for example be caused by a user closing their
laptop. Or a colab worker being disconnected.

Dead tasks do not carry a lot of information (they have no
associated message) and there are a lot of them.

But the fact that a task was declared dead can explain why a pgn file
was not uploaded. So it might still be useful to have a record of
them.

Title/Message:
Make lock file system more robust.

We may have several processes reading from and writing to the lock file
at the same time with potentially unpredictable consequences
(especially on windows). We now refactor the file IO operations
and put them in a try: except: bracket.

We also change the logic:

At the start of the worker we tolerate an invalid or non-existing
lock file since we intend to replace it with one of our own.
Once  we have started, we now only accept a valid lock file
containing our own PID.

Also: the name of the lock file is not a global variable anymore.

Also: send stderr to devnull on Linux. Like it is done on
Windows.

Title/Message:
A very primitive locking implementation.

We don't want two copies of the worker running in the
same directory.

The most natural way to achieve this would be to use a lock file.

Unfortunately Python doesn't have a cross platform file locking api.
So we just look for the existence of a lock file.
We do this when starting the worker (which is racy) and also
(as a fallback) before requesting a new task
(in that case we also check that the content of the lock file
is different from the current pid).

Title/Message:
Use the subprocess context manager

The context manager in the `.__exit__()` automatically:
 - closes the standard file descriptors
 - waits the process

Use `OSerror` and `SubprocessError` to catch an exception
from the context `.__enter__()`:
```
try:
  with Popen() as p:
     <body>
except (OSError, SubprocessError) as e:
   <handle exception in Popen()>
```

Use `ExitStack()` to deal with conditional context managers.

Title/Message:
Bug fix for purges with crashes and time losses.

The new purging logic purges workers (based on their residuals), not tasks.
So the current code which sets the residual to 8 for a task with several
crashes has no effect anymore (since it does not change the residual of the worker).

The implemented solution is to start purge_run() with a loop which filters
tasks with crashes and time losses, and then to compute the worker
based residuals (since these will be affected by the preliminary filtering).

Fixes #1058.
Author: Michel Van den Bergh

Title/Message:
Refactor purging logic and overhaul the residuals computation.

The computation of bad_workers is now done inside purge_run(),
where it logically belongs.

As a side effect of the refactoring it is now easy to have
different purging criteria for auto purging and manual purging.

As a proof of concept we have set the purging criteria for
manual purging to p=0.01 and residual=4.5, whereas for auto purging
(disabled by default) we have set them to p=0.001 and residual=7.0.

We also use a different logic for computing residuals because the
previous residuals (defined as the maximum of the absolute values
of the Pearson adjusted residuals in a row) have an unknown distribution.
Now we compute (conceptually) for every row in the chi2 table the
chi2 value of the 2x3 table obtained by that row and the sum of
the other rows. This chi2 value follows a chi2 distribution with
two degrees of freedom (under the null hypothesis that the workers are
homogeneous). To keep some compatibility with the previous
residuals, we convert the chi2 value to a standard normal
value.

To give an indication of the severity of a residual, Fishtest
uses a coloring scheme. However this coloring scheme was created
when far fewer workers were active. These days most of the
yellow and red residuals are just the result of statistical
fluctuations and as a result nobody pays any attention to them.

In this PR we update the coloring scheme. More precisely we color
residuals according to the p=0.05 and p=0.01 thresholds, but
using the Bonferroni correction, which divides these p-values
by the number of workers.

The pending flag is True when a task is not finished.
It was always redundant since it can be recomputed

pending flag says.

Title/Message:
Get rid of worker_key altogether.

The worker key tries to solve two unrelated problems:

(1) Long ago workers did not have to a unique key, so a substitute

(2) The unique key is not suitable for displaying, and perhaps should

Title/Message:
Document and refactor request_task.

In master "request_task()" is a large for loop which contains
a large if. We get rid of the if. This makes the code
much more readable.

The current structure is

run_found=False
for run in self.task_runs:
     # comment1
     if excluding_condition1:
         continue
     # comment2
     if excluding_condition2:
         continue
     ...
     run_found=True
     break

if not run_found:
     return

(now create a new task for the run that was found)

This should be a non-functional change.

Sort "task_runs" in request_update() at the correct place.

Title/Message:
Correct the chi2 p-value computation for an unbalanced book.

Currently the chi2 test assumes that the games in a task are independently
drawn from a trinomial distribution. This assumption is no longer
valid for an unbalanced book. This is very visible from the p-values
which are often > 99%. Under the null hypothesis p-values should be
uniformly distributed.

Since currently the ww and ll frequencies will be too small for
the chi2 test to be valid, we coalesce them with the wd and ld frequencies.

The main test page still shows the trinomial wdl frequencies. This will be
addressed in a separate PR.

Author: Tom Vijlbrief

Title/Message:
List SPRT bounds in "normalized Elo" on the raw stats page.

Normalized Elo is inversely proportional
to the square root of the number of games
it takes on average to detect a given strength
difference with a given level of significance.

In case of a perfectly balanced book and
small Elo differences normalized Elo is
approximately equal to

logistic_elo/sqrt(1-draw_ratio)

In other words if the draw ratio is zero,
the book is perfectly balanced
and Elo differences are small then
normalized Elo and logistic Elo coincide.

The theory behind normalized Elo is discussed here

http://hardy.uhasselt.be/Fishtest/normalized_elo.pdf

Compared to loc. cit. we have settled on using
an additional normalization factor

800/log(10)=347.43558552260146

which has the effect that normalized Elo and logistic Elo
are easier to compare (as explained above).

We also convert the former sensitivity field to normalized Elo.

Hopefully using this conversion the field will become
easier to interpret.

The purpose of the sensitivity field is to compare opening books.
The opening book influences both Elo and the draw ratio. By expressing
the result of a test in normalized Elo one can compare different
books.

Title/Message:
Fix SyntaxWarning: "is" with a literal

https://docs.python.org/3.8/whatsnew/3.8.html#changes-in-python-behavior

The compiler now produces a SyntaxWarning when identity checks (is and is not)
are used with certain types of literals (e.g. strings, numbers).
These can often work by accident in CPython, but are not guaranteed by the
language spec.
The warning advises users to use equality tests (== and !=) instead.

Title/Message:
Use the string literal '' as iter() sentinel

File objects for stdin, stdout and stderr by default are opened in bynary mode
and require a byte string literal b'' as iter() sentinel.

We have opened the file objects for stdout and stderr in text mode using the
"universal_newlines=True" argument in subprocess.Popen() so use the string
literal '' as iter() sentinel. Using b'' as sentinel is wrong and floods the
queue with void lines.

Drop the unnecessary closing of the stdout pipe, already done in kill_process()

Title/Message:
Enable a new algorithm for choosing SPSA hyperparameters.

This PR adds a checkbox to the "New Test" form. Checking this option
will rewrite the hyperparameters furnished by the tuning branch in
such a way that the SPSA tune will finish within 0.5 Elo from the optimum
(with 95% probability) assuming the function 'parameters->Elo'
is quadratic and varies 2 Elo per parameter over each specified
parameter interval. The hyperparameters are relatively conservative
and their performance will degrade gracefully if the actual variation
is different.  The theoretical basis for choosing the hyperparameters is
given in this document

https://github.com/vdbergh/spsa_simul/blob/master/doc/theoretical_basis.pdf

The formulas can be checked by simulation which is done here

https://github.com/vdbergh/spsa_simul

It is important for the current version of the algorithm to be able to
estimate the draw ratio. The PR uses a heuristic method to do so which
makes various assumptions: book='noob_3moves.epd', contempt=24,
threads=1 and no nodestime.

Title/Message:
Some code cleanup in the worker

The worker code is serial and hence in principle
quite simple. Unfortunately it has grown organically
and currently it is not so easy too follow anymore.
This makes the idea of adding new types of tests
rather unattractive.

This is PR is the first timid attempt at cleaning
up some of the worker code.

This version of the worker should be functionally
equivalent to version 75

The most notable changes are

- The global variable old_stats is eliminated. The fact
that such a global variable exists needlessly complicates the
logic of the worker code.

- Trinomial and pentanomial frequencies are
now kept in sync for all types of tests. This simplifies
the code a lot.

- More asserts have been added.

Title/Message:
Worker changes to allow batching.

A new quantity "batch_size" is defined.

In principle batch_size is the number of games that have to be
completed by the worker before an update is sent to the server.
However for sprt and numgames tests it is actually twice the
number of completed game pairs.

batch_size for sprt is communicated by the server. The reason
is that for the sprt algorithm to be theoretically correct all
workers have to use the same batch size.

For other tests batch_size is currently set by the worker to twice the
number of games it is capable of running concurrently.

This is equal to the number of cores reserved for the worker,
divided by the number of threads used by the engines.

Title/Message:
Add index to flag_cache, auto-expire after 7 days, new create_indexes.py

- Add indexes to flag and user caches for faster lookups and lower CPU
- IP lookups expire after 7 days using a MongoDB TTL index
- create_indexes.py now takes a list of collection names as arguments
  - since it's rare to need to re-create ALL indexes
  - by default, it prints the indexes on all collections
  - for each collection name given, it drops then creates indexes on it

Strictly speaking, the index on IP in flag_cache should be a unique index,
but practically a non-unique index avoids race conditions since there's a
delay between the lookup and inserting a new document, and documents in
this collection auto-expire anyways.

See MongoDB docs for more info on TTL indexes:

Title/Message:
Iterate through runs using range queries in update users scripts

Using skip for mongodb collections is inefficient for iterating through
large collections. It's better to use range queries on an indexed field.

See https://docs.mongodb.com/manual/reference/method/cursor.skip/#using-range-queries

This will only result in a significant speedup when iterating through a
large number of documents in a collection.

A quick benchmark on a $5 VPS when iterating through ~75,000 runs

Before:
Num runs processed: 74887
Successfully updated 1200 users

real	1m46.332s
user	0m22.695s
sys	0m0.744s

After:
Num runs processed: 74887
Successfully updated 1200 users

real	0m21.008s
user	0m16.653s
sys	0m0.444s

Title/Message:
Better overshoot correction.

The theoretical properties of an SPRT are established under the
assumption that updates are continuous.

To have accurate agreement with the predictions, when the updates are
discrete, one has to estimate the expected "overshoot" and terminate
the SPRT a bit early, accordingly.  Unfortunately, to the best of our
knowledge, overshoot estimation is (surprisingly) computationally expensive.

Moreover in the case of a GSPRT there is the added complication of
unknown parameters and these have to be continuously estimated from
the sample. This more or less means that the expected overshoot
estimation has to be performed after every update, which is
prohibitively expensive (IMHO, doing it only when we are "close" to
one of the boundaries would lead to messy and possibly fragile code).

A theoretical formula for the expected overshoot is: Siegmund -
Sequential Analysis - Corollary 8.33. Like other such formulas, it is
difficult to evaluate theoretically, but the result can be very easily
estimated, with only a few lines of code, from the ongoing test itself.
This "dynamic overshoot estimation" is implemented in this commit.

That this works very well can be verified by simulation. A multi-threaded
simulator written in C can be found here.

https://github.com/vdbergh/simul

Example:

$ ./simul --elo0 0 --elo1 10 --elo 0

yields

...
sims=20001904 pass=0.050322[0.050175,0.050469] ...
...

whereas

$ ./simul --elo0 0 --elo1 10 --elo 0 --noovcor

yields

...
sims=20000943 pass=0.048530[0.048385,0.048674] ...
...

(the confidence interval is 3 sigma).

Obviously the version with overshoot correction is much more accurate.

Currently Fishtest uses an approximate formula for overshoot
correction which is actually not even asymptotically correct, although
it works well for small Elo differences. However for larger Elo
differences it starts to break down. This is undesirable as people may
copy the Fishtest code and apply it in a different context.

In the implementation the SPRT() function in stat_util.py now takes an
sprt dictionary as argument. This dictionary may optionally contain a
subdictionary with dynamic overshoot data which is updated in-place.
It is assumed that SPRT() is called after each finished game (trinomial)
or game pair (pentanomial). But calling SPRT() multiple times with
the same parameters is safe and skipped updates are also handled sensibly.
After a purge the overshoot data is deleted. Deleting the overshoot data
is always safe as it simply means that the test is carried out with error
probabilities that are slightly smaller than the assigned ones.

The actual overshoot estimates can be found on the raw statistics
page. Note that the estimate corresponding to the test outcome (H0 or H1)
is typically the most accurate.

Title/Message:
On the raw stats page give estimates for the DD and WL probabilities.

Note that here WL really means WL+LW.

If p5[0..2] are the pentanomial probabilities and d
is the draw ratio then the probability of DD is equal to
dd=d-(p5[1]+p5[3])/2.

The probability of WL is then equal to
p[2]-dd.

Title/Message:
Make the worker calculate the pentanomial frequencies.

There are no server changes in this patch.

The updated worker will send the pentanomial frequencies
to the server and the server will faithfully store them in
its databaese as it does with all information received from
the client.

The actual logic added to the worker is quite minor.
A dictionary "rounds" keeps track of the finished games. For every
finished game pair (which consists of an odd numbered game
and the next even numbered game) the pentanomial frequencies
are updated.

Since sending incorrect frequencies to the server would
be quite distastrous, a lot of sanity checking is done to
make sure that the pentanomial frequencies are consistent
with the trinomial frequencies provided by cutechess itself.

Title/Message:
Fix "divide by zero" warnings improving chi2 computing for unusual cases

These unusual cases trigger a "divide by zero" RunTimeWarning:
 - run with only one worker:
   skip the test for the workers homogeneity and return p-value="nan" to avoid autopurge
 - total WLD has only one type of result (e.g. only wins):
   the workers are identical wrt the test, return the expected statistical values
 - total WLD has two type of result (e.g. wins missing):
   the workers are identical wrt the missing result type, reshape the data to avoid the "divide by zero"

Title/Message:
Handle test stop, restart in statistics update

When a test is stopped and restarted (by a modify) this
can cause many runs (30 days period) to be counted twice.
This happens only when the restarted test was the only new
finished test at the last execution of this script.
When the test is restarted before the script is executed
then there is also no error condition.

This can be fixed by storing also all older run-ids,
with a small performance impact (bigger MongoDb table).

Note that tasks in the restarted test are counted twice
when the error condition happens. This should be very rare.
Author: Tom Vijlbrief

Title/Message:
Change SPRT parameters for standard test

Following the discussion here https://github.com/official-stockfish/Stockfish/issues/1859, we aim at

    Improve precision, i.e. discard zero or negative patches and accept positive ones with higher margin

    Manage resource consumption.

After various simulations, here are results for different sets of SPRT parameters:

| Limits | [0,5] + [0,5]  | [0.5, 4.5] + [0,3.5] | [1,4] + [0,3]  | [0.5, 4] + [0, 3] | [0.5, 4] + [0, 3.5] | [0.4, 4.4] + [0, 3.2] |
| ------------- | ------------- | ------------- | ------------- | ------------- | ------------- | ------------- |
| 0 ELO pass prob | 0.0025 | 0.00123 | 0.00036 | 0.0011 | 0.0011 | 0.0014 |
| 1 ELO pass prob | 0.0744 | 0.1002 | 0.0805 | 0.1451 | 0.1183 | 0.1276 |
| +1 ELO rejectance ratio | 0.8201 | 0.7547 | 0.7625 | 0.6718 | 0.7049 | 0.7137 |
| +1.5 ELO rejectance ratio | 0.6310 | 0.5160 | 0.4865 | 0.3968 | 0.4249 | 0.4679 |
| +2 ELO rejectance ratio | 0.3936| 0.2709 | 0.2026 | 0.1700 | 0.1819 | 0.2374 |
| total ELO gain ratio | 1.0 | 1.3192 | 1.2373 | 1.7596 | 1.5664 | 1.5523 |
| -0 ELO acceptance ratio | 2.5 e-04 | 9.1e-05 | 2.2e-0.5 | 1.0 e-04 |  7.77 e-05 | 1.0 e-04 |
| Avg. STC cost | 18431 | 24456 | 34574 | 30936 | 30936 | 25110 |
| Avg. STC + LTC Cost | 27931 | 38039 | 45286 | 50604 | 46093 | 42990 |

From the table above, there is consensus that [0.5, 4.5] + [0, 3.5] pair is the best balance between improved sensitivity and resource consumption.

This patch makes the above parameters the default.

A big thank to all the people involved, particularly to @vondele and @vdbergh for developing and tuning the simulation tool, @Alayan-stk-2, @Chess13234, @xoto10, @Vizvezdenec and @NKONSTANTAKIS for the great and high quality discussion.
Author: Marco Costalba

Title/Message:
Catch the kill process error

Print an error message and pass the execution if the kill of the process fails.
The kill of the process is used as safety measure against a hanging process.
At the moment all the running processes seems to run and close fine,
so we are always trying to kill an already closed process.
With a WSL worker that run a SPSA test when the kill fails is raised
an exception that stops the execution for some seconds slowing the test.

Refactoring of 'try: except:' code as suggested by @tomtor
Change of the message as suggested by @vondele and @Stefano80

Title/Message:
Retire worker reconnect logic

When a worker disconnects from fishtest because of errors
and reconnects without being restarted (it gets a new ID
on restart) it is handed it's old job, unless it was
already assigned to another worker.

This situation is rare and the logic requires scanning all
tasks handed out.

https://github.com/glinscott/fishtest/pull/186 increased
the speed by remembering active task for each worker,
but this information is lost on a fishtest reboot.

Benefit from the current code is minimal so retire it.

Title/Message:
Limit request_task concurrency

A request_task call takes about 150ms (7 per second).

The worker randomizes calls in a 1 to 30s interval.

With 200 workers or more the request queue might consume
all threads, so limit concurrency to 4 requests.

The client side HTTP connection pool creates unnecessary load on server because when connection pool is not fully occupied, previously created connections are not reused.
We are reporting to server single-threaded, meaning that we'd never use more than one connection ever, pooling more than one of them makes no sense.

Title/Message:
Cache Run data and rewrite request_task in Python

The idea is simple, there is no need to read Run data more than once
from MongoDb, because we are the only one updating.

The only exceptions are:

* request_task, which executes a MongoDb query that modifies the database,
  so the Run data cache is invalidated.
* scavenge.py (new internal implementation for active Runs in this PR)
* update_users.py (does not write Run data)

This PR will also reduce the write frequency from update_task which is
executed hundreds of times each second and overwrites the data it has
just written a few milliseconds earlier. These writes are now buffered
and a buffer is flushed every second.

In addition rewrite and speedup request_task by executing the selection
logic in Python.
Author: Tom Vijlbrief

Title/Message:
Set max waitress connections to max nr of workers

Waitress default is 100.

If we have 200 workers with 8 cores and TC = 10s+0.1s
then this results in about 160 game result updates per second.

If a few expensive requests like the /tests, api/request_run or
api/request_spsa cause a delay of more then 0.625s then requests
will be dropped because the backlog is > 100 requests

Most of these dropped requests could have been processed quickly
and each worker will never have more than one outstanding request.
In addition default worker timeout is 5s.

Raising max connections from 100 to 500 does better match
current number of workers.
Author: Tom Vijlbrief

Title/Message:
Increase default SPRT game limit to 1000000

Currently, SPRT tests have a 128000 game limit, meaning that at most 128
workers can be assigned to a test, unless the limit is manually
increased. With the recent increase of fishtest machines, we are hitting
this limit quite often. The 128 chunks can get assigned quickly when the
test has barely started. As a result, some machines become idle.

This patch allows 1000 chunks to be assigned to a test by default.

Title/Message:

because these are not used in the recalculation.
This safes an additional 50% in traffic.

Author: Werner Fenchel

Author: Werner Fenchel

Title/Message:
randomized rounding for spsa

spsa converts floating point parameter values to integers via round(),
which is dicontinuous.  This patch adds randomized rounding,
which converts x+p (where x is integer and p is within [0,1)) to
x with probability 1-p and x+1 with probability p (thus we get back x+p
in expectation), which is continuous.
Author: Werner Fenchel

Title/Message:
treat boundaries symmetrically in spsa

prior to this patch, spsa boudnary treatment has the following two
properties:
* samples on either side of the iterate are clipped independently,
  meaning the sampling distribution is not symmetric about the current
  parameter.
* After clipping, it's possible to have a value exactly at the boundary.

This is bad because spsa interprets a draw as "do nothing", meaning
parameters are not updated.  but that only makes sense if the present
parameters are the average of the parameters tried in the test, which is
not the clase with the old clipping.

The second point is bad if one believes the first point is bad (causes
excessive asymmetry).

So this patch introduces clipping which is always symmetric.  It is
moreover cautious to not move all the way to the boundary when doing
this update.
Author: Werner Fenchel

Title/Message:
fix base_nps in SMP tests with HT

In verify_signature 'concurrency' was wrongly set to 'games_concurrency' instead of 'games_concurrency * threads'

In verify_signature() are started 2 instance of the engine:
- the first one with 'go infinite' and number of threads 'concurrency - 1': in order to load the CPU
- the second one with 'bench' and one thread: in order to compute bench signature and bench nps

In this way:
1. worker with virtual cores are rated correctly in SMP tests
2. worker without virtual cores are rated with the correct setting for TurboBoost (minor effect)

Tested with my worker (4-cores with HT)

With 'concurrency = 3', in all tests, my worker is rated @ 2.24 Mnps

With 'concurrency = 7'
  a. in 1-thread tests, the worker is rated @ 1.40 Mnps (TC scaled as with 7 slow cores)
  b. in 7-threads tests, the worker is rated @ 1.40 Mnps (TC scaled as with 7 slow cores)

Before the fix, with 'concurrency = 7' 
  c. in 7-threads tests, the worker was rated @ 2.24 Mnps (TC scaled as with 7 fast cores, wrong!)

Title/Message:
move -srand before -openings

cutechess currently honors -srand in -openings only if placed earlier in
the arguments; this may change soon but updating now just in case.
Author: Werner Fenchel

Title/Message:
Feed a random seed to cutechess.

Cutechess presently uses the current time, in seconds, to seed its RNG.
This makes it very easy for various machines in fishtest to choose the
same random seed on the same workload, particularly when a large number
of machines join a machine pool for a specific test.

The fix here is to pass a random integer to cutechess via the "-srand"
option.  A platform-independent seed is chosen using os.urandom(),
which raises an exception if a randomness source is unavailable.

Cutechess only uses 32 bits of random state (a "quint32"), and the
parser for -srand requires an unsigned integer (although the
Mersenne::initialize routine just takes an int), so the routine here
generates an unsigned integer.

Issue originally discovered by VoyagerOne at
https://groups.google.com/forum/#!topic/fishcooking/CW7Vlwur8CQ
Author: Werner Fenchel

between the maximum game duration, and the time an unattended PC
must wait until the hanging process is being killed.
Author: joergoster

Title/Message:
Restore LTC at 60 seconds

The sensible point of a LTC game is the average search depth (specially at midgame) not the average game duration.

Scalability issue are more and more important and the number of tests that pass STC and fail LTC is sensible (even now with SPRT[0,5] for both cases). This means that we really want to test a patch at a good average search depth rate. Ideally we want an even higher value of LTC, but given our current resoruces 60 seconds is an acceptable compromise.

This patch restores average search depth and has the draw back of increasing testing time by 40 secs on average. This is more then acceptable IMO considering the current rate of tests that fail LTC after STC (scalability sensible) and the fact that only few tests reach LTC, so total testing time is not so impacted.
Author: Marco Costalba

Merge pull request #59 from lucasart/increment

Scale increment
Author: Gary Linscott

Title/Message:
Scale increment

Without that we cannot test time management patches correctly, because each
worker uses a different increment/base ratio.

This problem is also known to cause chi-square to fail for tcs where the
increment is not small respective to the base, like 5+0.05 for example
(for the same reason).

Now with C++11 std::chrono, SF uses a sub millisecond precision on every
platform. The only constraint is that the Timer thread only checks for
time every 5 msec, but that's still 10x less than our 50msec increment,
so no risk to go below that.
Author: lucasart

Title/Message:
Merge pull request #58 from lucasart/pgo

PGO
Author: Gary Linscott

Title/Message:
PGO

We've (re)learnt recently that the compiler can really optimize differently
with PGO, making use of profiling information collected at runtime. Whether a
patch is a clear speedup or a clear speed regression can be radically different
with and without PGO. Often fishtest is being used to verify non functional
changes that are supposed to speedup the engine (or simplifications that are
supposed not to slow it down). To be able to rely on fishtest for that, it must
use PGO.
Author: lucasart

Merge pull request #42 from FieryDragonLord/master

Display a simple message when there are no tasks.
Author: Gary Linscott

Title/Message:
Display a simple message when there are no tasks.

When there are no tasks, the worker script will simply sleep and wait until there is a task. However, no output is generated when this happens, so the user may think an error has occurred. This change adds a message so that the user knows the worker is waiting for a task.

Note that as implemented, the worker will display the message repeatedly if it needs to wait for an extended period of time.
Author: FieryDragonLord

Title/Message:
First cut at adding CLOP interface

Added a new glue script that support multiple
functions according to the command line arguments:

1) start_clop: Starts CLOP with given parameters
2) write_result: Updates the result of a played game
3) Called by CLOP to start a new game

There is a buffer (a clopdb) that disjoints the script
from the fishtest framework. In particular games to run
are queued in clopdb, in async fashion fishtest peeks from
clopdb a game to run, runs it and then updates the result
in the same clopdb row. Once result is updated is feeded
back to CLOP and corresponding row is removed from the DB
Author: Marco Costalba

Title/Message:
Change default book to 8moves_GM.pgn

As Adam Hair says:

"I can share with the group a pgn of 48,491 games that are 8 moves deep.
These games came from GM games that Norm Pollock collected and shares at
his website (the same games that Martin used to make the TCEC book used
in stage 1). I used some of the top engines to filter out positions that
may be too unbalanced. The final position of each truncated game is unique,
so that it is a source of 48,491 unique starting positions. Also, I used
some of the top engines to filter out positions that may be too unbalanced.
It is not perfect, but it may be suitable for the group's purposes.

Title/Message:
Fix run_games exception

Currently after the first exception we send api/failed_task
to host that set the task as not active. So when we retry (up
to five times) and in case succed, when we send updated_task
result is ignored because task is not active anymore.

So fix it allowing the worker to retry forever but redo the
full loop, starting from getting a new task.

Title/Message:
Always disconnect when finishing a task

After a task is finished the worker always diconnects
from the host.

This has the effect to correctly catch CTRL+C under windows,
that currently simply quits worker.py without rising any
exception and so leaving a stale machine on host.

But in general terms it is also IMHO a better way to handle
normal task processing where we each job transaction become
self contained and protocol is more consistent:

start job -> run games -> end job

As a side note, eventually a rename of API from failed_task to
end_task or something similar would be more consostent but
becuase is a not back compatible change and breaks the API
shall be scheduled for a future 1.0
Author: Marco Costalba

Title/Message:
Retire any reference to a specific IP address

And clarify security policy of the framework.
In particulary we can have 2 cases:

1) User app (like a worker task) runs locally on the same
   machine of the other components (Celery, MangoDb, etc)

2) User app runs on another machine and acceses the host
   through a network connection.

In the first case there is nothing to do, in the second case
user shall setup a ssh connection with port forwarding, see
README for details.

In both cases fishtest is agonstic about the remote host and
even does not know (or care) if the components are remote or
local.
Author: Marco Costalba
